T1  - Drought, smallpox, and emergence of Leishmania braziliensis in northeastern Brazil.
T3  - Comment in: Emerg Infect Dis. 2011 Feb;17(2):326-7; author reply 327. doi: 10.3201/eid1702.091823 PMID: 21291626 [https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/21291626]
DO  - https://dx.doi.org/10.3201/eid1506.071331
A1  - Sousa, Anastacio Q
A1  - Pearson, Richard
Y1  - 2009//
N1  - Comment in (CIN)
N2  - Cutaneous leishmaniasis caused by Leishmania (Vianna) braziliensis is a major health problem in the state of Ceara in northeastern Brazil. We propose that the disease emerged as a consequence of the displacement of persons from Ceara to the Amazon region following the Great Drought and smallpox epidemic of 1877-1879. As the economic and social situation in Ceara deteriorated, approximately 55,000 residents migrated to the Amazon region to find work, many on rubber plantations. Those that returned likely introduced L. (V.) brazilensis into Ceara, where the first cases of cutaneous leishmaniasis were reported early in the 20th century. The absence of an animal reservoir in Ceara, apart from dogs, supports the hypothesis. The spread of HIV/AIDS into the region and the possibility of concurrent cutaneous leishmaniasis raise the possibility of future problems.
